.SH NAME
polyglot\-java \- Java starter and maintenance workflow
.SH PURPOSE
This page explains the supported Java workflow in
polyglot\-devcontainers.
.SH WHEN TO USE
Read this page when working in Java starters or Java proving paths.
.SH PRIMARY COMMANDS
.IP
.EX
task init
task ci
task deps:plan
task deps:report
.EE
.SH WORKFLOW
The current Java path is Gradle\-first.
.PP
In the published \f[CR]java\f[R] starter image:
.IP \(bu 2
the image already contains Java, Gradle, and the scanner toolchain
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]task init\f[R] still prepares project\-local state such as
\f[CR].gradle\f[R], build outputs, and dependency locks in the mounted
workspace
.IP \(bu 2
this is expected because the image ships the toolchain, while the
project workspace owns the resolved build state
.PP
Safe default workflow:
.IP "1." 3
open the container
.IP "2." 3
run \f[CR]task init\f[R]
.IP "3." 3
do the work
.IP "4." 3
run \f[CR]task ci\f[R]
.PP
Dependency\-oriented workflow:
.IP "1." 3
run \f[CR]task deps:inventory\f[R]
.IP "2." 3
run \f[CR]task deps:plan\f[R]
.IP "3." 3
run \f[CR]task deps:report\f[R]
.IP "4." 3
use \f[CR]task upgrade\f[R] when you want the validated Gradle update
path
.IP "5." 3
rerun \f[CR]task lint\f[R], \f[CR]task test\f[R], and
\f[CR]task scan\f[R]
.PP
Repository\-owned scenario slice:
.IP \(bu 2
from the repository root, run
\f[CR]task scenarios:java\-maintenance\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
inspect \f[CR].artifacts/scenarios/java\-gradle\-maintenance.md\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
treat \f[CR]task upgrade\f[R] in
\f[CR]examples/java\-maintenance\-example\f[R] as the manual follow\-on
execution step after reading the evidence
.IP \(bu 2
from the repository root, run
\f[CR]task scenarios:java\-openrewrite\f[R] to validate the
non\-mutating OpenRewrite proof
.IP \(bu 2
inspect \f[CR].artifacts/scenarios/java\-openrewrite\-dry\-run.log\f[R]
and \f[CR].artifacts/scenarios/java\-openrewrite\-dry\-run.patch\f[R]
.SH SEMANTIC REFACTORING WITH OPENREWRITE
The Java path includes \f[CR]rewrite:dry\-run\f[R] and
\f[CR]rewrite:run\f[R] tasks backed by the OpenRewrite Gradle plugin.
These tasks are separate from and orthogonal to \f[CR]task upgrade\f[R].
.SS rewrite:dry-run vs task upgrade
Use \f[B]task rewrite:dry\-run\f[R] when you want to:
.IP \(bu 2
inspect what OpenRewrite recipes would change in source code
.IP \(bu 2
check whether any automated refactoring is available before committing
to a source\-level change
.IP \(bu 2
run a non\-destructive report at any point in the workflow without risk
of modifying files
.PP
\f[CR]rewrite:dry\-run\f[R] maps to Gradle\[cq]s \f[CR]rewriteDryRun\f[R]
task.
It writes a unified diff report under
\f[CR]build/reports/rewrite/rewrite.patch\f[R] and
prints a summary to stdout but does \f[B]not\f[R] modify any source file.
Safe to run at any time.
.PP
Use \f[B]task upgrade\f[R] when you want to:
.IP \(bu 2
update dependency version numbers in \f[CR]build.gradle.kts\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
refresh the dependency lockfile after version changes
.IP \(bu 2
run the full lint/test/scan verification loop after version updates
.PP
\f[CR]task upgrade\f[R] uses the \f[CR]use\-latest\-versions\f[R] and
\f[CR]dependencyUpdates\f[R] Gradle plugins to propose and apply version
bumps.
It does \f[B]not\f[R] modify Java source code.
.SS When to use rewrite:run
\f[CR]rewrite:run\f[R] is a \f[B]mutating\f[R] operation.
It modifies Java source files in place.
Always follow it with \f[CR]task ci\f[R] to verify the build is still
green.
.PP
If \f[CR]task ci\f[R] fails after \f[CR]rewrite:run\f[R], revert the
source changes and narrow the active recipe before re\-applying.
.PP
If a \f[CR]rewrite:run\f[R] execution modifies \f[CR]build.gradle.kts\f[R]
(possible with dependency\-version or build\-file recipes), run
\f[CR]task init\f[R] before \f[CR]task ci\f[R] to regenerate the
dependency lockfile.
.SS OpenRewrite workflow
.IP
.EX
task rewrite:dry\-run   # inspect proposed changes \[em] safe, non\-destructive
task rewrite:run       # apply changes \[em] MUTATING; follow with task ci
task ci                # verify build is green after rewrite:run
.EE
